      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the mystery of the student loan principal and the sly little interest that keeps playing hide and seek! Well, my friend, imagine your student loan as a mountain of gold guarded by a mischievous goblin. Every month, you send a brave knight (that's you, paying the monthly amount) to the goblin's lair to take a chunk of gold. But the goblin, being a sly creature, only takes the gold that was there before you sent the knight, not the new gold you just brought. So, the mountain of gold (your principal) doesn't shrink as much as you'd hope because the goblin is only interested in the old gold, not the new gold you bring each month. The goblin's trick is called \"interest on a declining balance.\" The goblin calculates the interest based on the remaining gold, not the total amount you owe. So, as you continue to send your knight, the goblin's interest keeps growing on the remaining gold, making it seem like the mountain isn't shrinking as fast as you'd like. But don't worry, brave knight, with time and patience, you'll eventually outsmart the goblin and claim your mountain of gold!",
